      </dates>
      <abstract><style face="normal" font="default" size="100%">Objective: To determine whether admission fibrinogen levels predict 30-day functional outcome in adults with isolated traumatic brain injury. Methods: Retrospective analysis of 215 consecutive patients. Fibrinogen 1.5 g/L at admission was defined as hypofibrinogenaemia. Primary outcome was Glasgow Outcome Scale at 30 days. Results: Hypofibrinogenaemia was present in 28% of patients and was independently associated with poor outcome (OR 3.1, 95% CI 1.8-5.4). Conclusions: Low fibrinogen at admission is a useful prognostic marker in isolated TBI.</style></abstract>
